 staff morale. These indicators assess aspects of performance that are not directly related to financial metrics and are used to supplement financial measures. By evaluating these qualitative factors, NFPIs provide a more comprehensive understanding of an organization's overall performance.\",2\n1052,\"\"\"FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (FPIS)\"\"\",\"\"\"Financial performance indicators (FPIs) include measures such as profitability, liquidity, efficiency, and gearing. These traditional performance measures focus on financial aspects such as return on capital, profit margins, and liquidity ratios.\"\"\",7\n1057,\"\"\"PROFIT MARGINS\"\"\",\"\"\"PROFIT MARGINS\"\" are a financial performance indicator that measures the profitability of an organization relative to its revenue. Profit margins relate profit to revenue and can be calculated at different levels of profit reported in the financial statements.\",3\n1067,\"\"\"LIQUIDITY RATIOS\"\"\",\"\"\"Liquidity ratios\"\" are financial performance indicators that measure an organization's ability to meet its short-term obligations. These ratios assess the organization's capacity to fulfill its liabilities as they become due. Operating cash flows are considered the ultimate measure of liquidity, reflecting the organization's ability to generate sufficient cash to cover its immediate financial commitments.\",2\n1078,\"\"\"GEARING RATIOS\"\"\",\"Gearing Ratios are financial performance indicators that measure the proportion of an organization's capital that is financed by debt. These ratios specifically assess the proportion of long-term borrowed funds, which pay a fixed return, relative to equity capital, also known as shareholders' funds. Gearing Ratios provide critical information about a company's financial risk due to its debt burden. Two commonly used Gearing Ratios are: Equity/Debt * 100, which gives gearing as a percentage, and Debt/Equity plus debt * 100.\",2\n1110,\"\"\"ASSET TURNOVER RATIOS\"\"\",\"\"\"Financial performance indicators that measure how efficiently an organisation uses its assets to generate revenue.\"\"\",1\n1109,\"\"\"RETURN ON CAPITAL\"\"\",\"\"\"A financial performance indicator that measures the profitability of an organisation relative to its capital.\"\"\",1\n1111,\"\"\"INTEREST COVER\"\"\",\"\"\"A financial performance indicator that measures an organisation's ability to meet its interest payments on debt.\"\"\",1\n1068,\"\"\"CURRENT RATIO\"\"\",\"The \"\"Current Ratio\"\" is calculated as the ratio of current assets to current liabilities at the end of a period. The formula for the current ratio is: Current ratio = Current assets (at period end) / Current liabilities (at period end). The purpose of the current ratio is to measure the adequacy of current assets to meet current liabilities without the need to raise additional finance. A ratio of less than 1 indicates that current liabilities exceed current assets.\",1\n1077,\"\"\"GEARING\"\"\",\"\"\"Gearing (or 'leverage') measures the portion of a company's finance provided by debt. The advantage of debt is that it is a relatively cheap source of financing. Providers of debt require a lower return than providers of equity finance because they face less risk, as they receive preferential repayment in the event of default. Interest on debt is also a tax-deductible expense, which further reduces the cost of debt. However, companies with too much debt (gearing) increase the risk of being unable to repay the debt's interest and principal.\"\"\",1\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\n90,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT\"\"\",\"\"\"BALANCED SCORECARD\"\"\",\"\"\"Performance measurement can be enhanced using the Balanced Scorecard methodology.\"\"\",28\n1039,\"\"\"NON-FINANCIAL PERFORMANCE INDICATORS (NFPIS)\"\"\",\"\"\"BALANCED SCORECARD\"\"\",\"\"\"Balanced Scorecard includes Non-financial performance indicators (NFPIs).\"\"\",24\n86,\"\"\"PERFORMANCE MEASUREMENT\"\"